{"title_page": "Cha Ca La Vong", "text_new": "'''Cha Ca La Vong''' '''(Ch\u1ea3 c\u00e1 L\u00e3 V\u1ecdng''' in Vietnamese) is a [[Vietnamese cuisine|Vietnamese]] grilled fish dish, originally from [[Hanoi]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/cha-ca-street-hanoi-vietnam/index.html|title=Cha Ca: An entire Hanoi street dedicated to one special dish|author1=Justin Solomon |author2=Kate Springer|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> The dish is traditionally made with [[hemibagrus]] (or ''ca lang'' in Vietnamese), which is a genus of [[catfish]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.afar.com/magazine/the-dish-worth-traveling-to-vietnam-for-and-it-isnt-pho|title=The Dish Worth Traveling to Vietnam For (and It Isn\u2019t Pho)|website=AFAR Media|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> The fish is cut into pieces and marinated in a [[turmeric]]-based sauce, which often includes [[shrimp paste]] or [[fish sauce]], [[ginger]], and [[Chili pepper|chilis peppers]]. Sometimes, [[saffron]] is used instead of turmeric. It is then lightly [[Grilling|grilled]] over [[charcoal]]. The dish is served in a hot pan coated with marinade sauce and herbs, particularly [[dill]]. Other herbs, such as [[Scallion|scallions]] or [[basil]], may be included. It is eaten with [[vermicelli]] [[rice noodles]] (''b\u00fan'' in Vietnamese)<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thanhniennews.com/travel/the-kings-of-cha-ca-12029.html|title=The kings of ch\u1ea3 c\u00e1|date=2011-06-03|website=Thanh Nien Daily|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> and [[Peanut|peanuts]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|last=Fabricant|first=Florence|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/30/dining/cha-ca-la-vong-a-dish-inspired-by-a-dive-in-hanoi.html|title=A Dish Inspired by a Dive in Hanoi|date=2012-05-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bonappetit.com/recipe/turmeric-fish-rice-noodles|title=Turmeric Fish with Rice Noodles and Herbs Recipe|last=Baraghani|first=Andy|website=Bon Appetit|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> Cha Ca La Vong is considered a luxury food item in Vietnam, as it is nearly exclusively served in restaurants and is not found in [[street food]].<ref name=\":1\" /> \n== History ==\nIn the 19th century, the Doan family were known to prepare grilled fish for their neighbors. The dish became so popular that their local community helped the family open a restaurant, named Cha Ca Va Long. The words \"Cha ca\" translate to \"grilled fish\" in Vietnamese. Meanwhile, \"La Vong\" was inspired by a local statue of [[Jiang Ziya]], also known as Lu Wang (pronounced as \"La Vong\" in Vietnamese), the fisherman-turned-politician who symbolized the potential for patient, talented people.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe restaurant opened on Hang Son Street in the [[Old Quarter, Hanoi|Old Quarter]] of Hanoi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/food-drink/restaurants/hanoi-cha-ca-la-vong-restaurant|title=The Fish to Fly Across the World For|website=Travel + Leisure|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> This was reportedly the same street where the Doan family had lived before opening the restaurant. Eventually, the restaurant became popular with [[colonial troops]] of [[French Indochina]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Copycat restaurants opened on the street with similar names, such as Cha Ca La Song. Other restaurants used the exact same name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/pacific-nw-magazine/this-tasty-vietnamese-fish-dish-has-the-best-name-ever-cha-ca-la-vong/|title=This tasty Vietnamese fish dish has the best name ever: Cha Ca La Vong|date=2015-05-15|website=The Seattle Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> For this reason, Hang Son was officially renamed Cha Ca.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nThe original Cha Ca Va Long restaurant is still open in Hanoi, where it only serves its signature dish, and guests eat from charcoal burners at communal tables.<ref name=\":3\" /> The restaurant was listed as a destination in the book ''1000 Places to Visit Before You Die''.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Categories == \n\n[[Category:Vietnamese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Hanoi]]\n[[Category:Fish dishes]]\n", "text_old": "'''Cha Ca La Vong''' '''(Ch\u1ea3 c\u00e1 L\u00e3 V\u1ecdng''' in Vietnamese) is a [[Vietnamese cuisine|Vietnamese]] grilled fish dish, originally from [[Hanoi]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/cha-ca-street-hanoi-vietnam/index.html|title=Cha Ca: An entire Hanoi street dedicated to one special dish|last=CNN|first=By Justin Solomon, Kate Springer|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> The dish is traditionally made with [[hemibagrus]] (or ''ca lang'' in Vietnamese), which is a genus of [[catfish]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.afar.com/magazine/the-dish-worth-traveling-to-vietnam-for-and-it-isnt-pho|title=The Dish Worth Traveling to Vietnam For (and It Isn\u2019t Pho)|website=AFAR Media|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> The fish is cut into pieces and marinated in a [[turmeric]]-based sauce, which often includes [[shrimp paste]] or [[fish sauce]], [[ginger]], and [[Chili pepper|chilis peppers]]. Sometimes, [[saffron]] is used instead of turmeric. It is then lightly [[Grilling|grilled]] over [[charcoal]]. The dish is served in a hot pan coated with marinade sauce and herbs, particularly [[dill]]. Other herbs, such as [[Scallion|scallions]] or [[basil]], may be included. It is eaten with [[vermicelli]] [[rice noodles]] (''b\u00fan'' in Vietnamese)<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thanhniennews.com/travel/the-kings-of-cha-ca-12029.html|title=The kings of ch\u1ea3 c\u00e1|date=2011-06-03|website=Thanh Nien Daily|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> and [[Peanut|peanuts]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|last=Fabricant|first=Florence|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/30/dining/cha-ca-la-vong-a-dish-inspired-by-a-dive-in-hanoi.html|title=A Dish Inspired by a Dive in Hanoi|date=2012-05-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bonappetit.com/recipe/turmeric-fish-rice-noodles|title=Turmeric Fish with Rice Noodles and Herbs Recipe|last=Baraghani|first=Andy|website=Bon Appetit|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> Cha Ca La Vong is considered a luxury food item in Vietnam, as it is nearly exclusively served in restaurants and is not found in [[street food]].<ref name=\":1\" /> \n== History ==\nIn the 19th century, the Doan family were known to prepare grilled fish for their neighbors. The dish became so popular that their local community helped the family open a restaurant, named Cha Ca Va Long. The words \"Cha ca\" translate to \"grilled fish\" in Vietnamese. Meanwhile, \"La Vong\" was inspired by a local statue of [[Jiang Ziya]], also known as Lu Wang (pronounced as \"La Vong\" in Vietnamese), the fisherman-turned-politician who symbolized the potential for patient, talented people.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe restaurant opened on Hang Son Street in the [[Old Quarter, Hanoi|Old Quarter]] of Hanoi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/food-drink/restaurants/hanoi-cha-ca-la-vong-restaurant|title=The Fish to Fly Across the World For|website=Travel + Leisure|language=EN|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> This was reportedly the same street where the Doan family had lived before opening the restaurant. Eventually, the restaurant became popular with [[colonial troops]] of [[French Indochina]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Copycat restaurants opened on the street with similar names, such as Cha Ca La Song. Other restaurants used the exact same name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/pacific-nw-magazine/this-tasty-vietnamese-fish-dish-has-the-best-name-ever-cha-ca-la-vong/|title=This tasty Vietnamese fish dish has the best name ever: Cha Ca La Vong|date=2015-05-15|website=The Seattle Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> For this reason, Hang Son was officially renamed Cha Ca.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nThe original Cha Ca Va Long restaurant is still open in Hanoi, where it only serves its signature dish, and guests eat from charcoal burners at communal tables.<ref name=\":3\" /> The restaurant was listed as a destination in the book ''1000 Places to Visit Before You Die''.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Categories == \n\n[[Category:Vietnamese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Hanoi]]\n[[Category:Fish dishes]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cha_Ca_La_Vong"}
